Deploy MoE-LLaVA Model in Amazon SageMaker

What is MoE-LLaVA model?

  • MoE-LLaVA is the Mixture of Experts for Large Vision-Language Models. Paper or resources for more information is this repo.
  • MoE_LLaVA achieves high performance with fewer parameters. A great open source alternative to GPT-4V.

Deployment of pre-trained Hugging Face models to AWS SageMaker

AWS SageMaker is a popular ML platform which allows engineers to train and deploy models. Its inference toolkit supports a straightforward way to deploy a hugging face transformers model.

If the pre-trained model has been integrated with Huggingface Python SDK, it can be easily deployed with the following code:

from sagemaker.huggingface.model import HuggingFaceModel

# Hub model configuration <https://huggingface.co/models>
hub = {
  'HF_MODEL_ID':'distilbert-base-uncased-distilled-squad', # model_id from hf.co/models
  'HF_TASK':'question-answering'                           # NLP task you want to use for predictions
}

# create Hugging Face Model Class
huggingface_model = HuggingFaceModel(
   env=hub,                                                # configuration for loading model from Hub
   role=role,                                              # IAM role with permissions to create an endpoint
   transformers_version="4.26",                             # Transformers version used
   pytorch_version="1.13",                                  # PyTorch version used
   py_version='py39',                                      # Python version used
)

# deploy model to SageMaker Inference
predictor = huggingface_model.deploy(
   initial_instance_count=1,
   instance_type="ml.m5.xlarge"
)

# example request: you always need to define "inputs"
data = {
"inputs": {
 "question": "What is used for inference?",
 "context": "My Name is Philipp and I live in Nuremberg. This model is used with sagemaker for inference."
 }
}

# request
predictor.predict(data)

More information can be found in Deploy models to Amazon SageMaker.

However, since MoE-LLaVA model was released on 2024â€“01â€“30, it has not been integrated as of now. We need a custom solution to deploy the model. Here we provide a way to create our own docker container to serve the model in SageMaker.

Step 0: create an ECR repo

Step 1: download the model artifacts

from huggingface_hub import snapshot_download

HF_MODEL_ID="LanguageBind/MoE-LLaVA-Phi2-2.7B-4e"

snapshot_download(HF_MODEL_ID, local_dir="moe-llava-phi2-2.7B", local_dir_use_symlinks=False)

Step 2: zip the model artifacts into model.tar.gz and upload it to a S3 bucket

tar -czvf model.tar.gz *

aws s3 cp model.tar.gz <s3-url>

Step 3: create requirements.txt

flask
gunicorn
boto3
flash-attention
deepspeed==0.12.6
moellava @ git+https://github.com/PKU-YuanGroup/MoE-LLaVA

Step 4: create Dockerfile

FROM debian:bullseye-slim

USER root

RUN apt-get update && apt-get upgrade -y
RUN apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends python3-pip

# to pip install mpi4y
RUN apt-get --fix-broken install
RUN apt-get install libopenmpi-dev mpich -y

# Set environment variables
# ensures that Python outputs everything that's printed directly to the terminal (so logs can be seen in real-time)
ENV PYTHONUNBUFFERED=TRUE
# ensures Python doesn't try to write .pyc files to disk (useful for improving performance in some scenarios)
ENV PYTHONDONTWRITEBYTECODE=TRUE
# Update PATH environment variable to include /opt/program directory
ENV PATH="/opt/program:${PATH}"

# install python
RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y python3-dev git curl
RUN ln -s /usr/bin/python3 /usr/bin/python

# Set the working directory in the Docker image to /opt/program
WORKDIR /opt/program

# Upgrade pip package manager to the latest version
RUN pip install --upgrade pip

# Get requirements.txt file and install packages
RUN pip install mpi4py
COPY ./requirements.txt /opt/program/requirements.txt
RUN pip install --no-cache-dir --upgrade -r requirements.txt

# Copy the source code of the application
COPY ./src /opt/program

USER nobody

ENV SM_MODEL_DIR /opt/ml/model

ENTRYPOINT ["gunicorn", "-b", ":8080", "prediction_script:app"]

Step 5: create src/prediction_script.py

import json
import os
import requests
import torch
from io import BytesIO
from PIL import Image
from flask import Flask, request
from moellava.constants import IMAGE_TOKEN_INDEX, DEFAULT_IMAGE_TOKEN
from moellava.conversation import conv_templates, SeparatorStyle
from moellava.model.builder import load_pretrained_model
from moellava.utils import disable_torch_init
from moellava.mm_utils import (
    tokenizer_image_token,
    KeywordsStoppingCriteria,
)

# Instantiate Flask app
app = Flask(__name__)

# Define the model path
# When you configure the model, you will need to specify the S3 location of your model artifacts.
# Sagemaker will automatically download, decompress and store the model's weights in the /opt/ml/model folder.
MODEL_PATH = os.environ["SM_MODEL_DIR"]

# Define the model name
# The model name can be difficult to work with.
# Instead of replying on this statement https://github.com/PKU-YuanGroup/MoE-LLaVA/blob/main/predict.py#L16C5-L16C54
# Let's hard code the model name
MODEL_NAME = "moe-llava-phi2-2.7B"


# Load the model
def model_fn(model_dir):
    disable_torch_init()
    tokenizer, model, processor, context_len = load_pretrained_model(
        model_dir,
        None,
        model_name=MODEL_NAME,
        load_8bit=False,
        load_4bit=False,
        device_map="auto",
        device="cuda",
        padding_side="right",
    )
    image_processor = processor["image"]
    return model, tokenizer, image_processor


# Unpack
model, tokenizer, image_processor = model_fn(MODEL_PATH)


# Define an endpoint for health check
@app.route("/ping", methods=["GET"])
def ping():
    return "", 200


# Define an endpoint for making predictions
@app.route("/invocations", methods=["POST"])
def predict():
    # Get data from the POST request
    data_str = request.get_data().decode("utf-8")

    # Convert data (string) to dictionary
    data_dict = json.loads(data_str)

    # Split the data into image and question
    image_file = data_dict.pop("image", data_dict)
    raw_prompt = data_dict.pop("question", data_dict)

    if image_file.startswith("http") or image_file.startswith("https"):
        response = requests.get(image_file)
        image_tensor = image_processor.preprocess(
            Image.open(BytesIO(response.content)).convert("RGB"), return_tensors="pt"
        )["pixel_values"].to(model.device, dtype=torch.float16)
    else:
        # TODO: verify if this is the correct way to load image from local file
        image = Image.open(image_file).convert("RGB")
        image_tensor = image_processor.preprocess(image, return_tensors="pt")[
            "pixel_values"
        ].to(model.device, dtype=torch.float16)

    inp = DEFAULT_IMAGE_TOKEN + "\n" + raw_prompt

    max_new_tokens = data_dict.pop("max_new_tokens", 1024)
    temperature = data_dict.pop("temperature", 0.2)

    conv_mode = "phi"  # phi or qwen or stablelm
    conv = conv_templates[conv_mode].copy()

    conv.append_message(conv.roles[0], inp)
    conv.append_message(conv.roles[1], None)

    prompt = conv.get_prompt()
    input_ids = (
        tokenizer_image_token(prompt, tokenizer, IMAGE_TOKEN_INDEX, return_tensors="pt")
        .unsqueeze(0)
        .cuda()
    )
    stop_str = conv.sep if conv.sep_style != SeparatorStyle.TWO else conv.sep2
    keywords = [stop_str]
    stopping_criteria = KeywordsStoppingCriteria(keywords, tokenizer, input_ids)

    with torch.inference_mode():
        output_ids = model.generate(
            input_ids,
            images=image_tensor,
            do_sample=True,
            temperature=temperature,
            max_new_tokens=max_new_tokens,
            use_cache=True,
            stopping_criteria=[stopping_criteria],
        )

    outputs = tokenizer.decode(
        output_ids[0, input_ids.shape[1] :], skip_special_tokens=True
    ).strip()
    return outputs

Step 6: build and push the docker image to ECR

docker build -f Dockerfile -t <ECR-repo-url>:latest .

docker push <ECR-repo-url>

Step 7: create a SageMaker model

It can be done in AWS console directly with the inference image in ECR and the model.tar.gz in S3 as 2 inputs.

The code snippet below takes ONLY the non-zipped (uncompressed) model artifacts as input to create the SageMaker model. More information can be found here.

model_name = "model-name"
sagemaker_role = "arn:aws:iam::123456789012:role/SageMakerExecutionRole"
container = "123456789012.dkr.ecr.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/inference-image:latest"

create_model_response = sagemaker_client.create_model(
    ModelName = model_name,
    ExecutionRoleArn = sagemaker_role,
    PrimaryContainer = {
        "Image": container,
        "ModelDataSource": {
            "S3DataSource": {
                "S3Uri": "s3://my-bucket/prefix/to/model/data/", 
                "S3DataType": "S3Prefix",
                "CompressionType": "None",
            },
        },
    },
)

Step 8: create a SageMaker endpoint

Now we can create the endpoint with the SageMaker model. Choose an instance with cuda GPU to host the model, e.g., ml.g5.xlarge.

Test the endpoint:

import boto3
import json

runtime = boto3.client('runtime.sagemaker')

sample_data = {"image" : "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/haotian-liu/LLaVA/main/images/llava_logo.png", "question" : "Describe the image and color details."}
sample_data_v2 = json.dumps(sample_data).encode()


response = runtime.invoke_endpoint(EndpointName='moe-llava-phi2-2-7b',
                                   ContentType='application/json',
                                   Body=sample_data_v2)
print(response['Body'].read())
